  "prompt": "What is the relation between frequency and time period?",
  "response": "Frequency and time period are inversely related. This means that as one increases, the other decreases, and vice versa.\n\n**Here's the relationship:**\n\n*   **Frequency (f):** The number of cycles or repetitions of a periodic event per unit of time. Measured in Hertz (Hz), which is cycles per second.\n\n*   **Time Period (T):** The time it takes for one complete cycle or repetition of a periodic event. Measured in seconds (s).\n\n**The formula connecting them is:**\n\n*   **f = 1 / T**  (Frequency equals one divided by the time period)\n\n*   **T = 1 / f**  (Time period equals one divided by the frequency)\n\n**In simpler terms:**\n\n*   If something happens very frequently (high frequency), the time between each event is short (short time period).\n*   If something happens rarely (low frequency), the time between each event is long (long time period).\n\n**Example:**\n\nImagine a pendulum swinging back and forth.\n\n*   If it swings back and forth 10 times per second (frequency = 10 Hz), then the time it takes for one complete swing is 1/10 of a second (time period = 0.1 seconds).\n*   If it swings back and forth once every 2 seconds (time period = 2 seconds), then the frequency is 1/2 Hz (0.5 Hz), meaning it completes half a swing per second.\n",
